Acceptance tests are the canary in the coal mine. If a demo case fails,
it means a fundamental calculation or rule is wrong. A demo case failure
is always a Critical-severity defect per the Layer 1 taxonomy, because
the expected values are hand-calculated from statute. There is no
ambiguity in what the right answer is.

> *Acceptance test tolerance: \$0.00. Every monetary value must match
> the hand calculation exactly. If there is a penny difference, it is
> investigated---it may reveal a rounding strategy discrepancy that
> affects thousands of members at scale.*

3\. Test Oracle Management

The test oracle---the source of expected values---is the most critical
component of the test framework. If the oracle is wrong, every test that
passes is a false assurance. Oracle management ensures the expected
values are correct, traceable, and maintained as rules evolve.

