3.2 Oracle Integrity Rules

The following rules protect oracle integrity:

1.  **Never record-then-assert.** Expected values are never generated by
    running the system and recording its output. This circular approach
    cannot detect defects.

2.  **Never copy from legacy.** Legacy system outputs are comparison
    data, not oracle data. A test that passes because it matches a
    legacy defect is worse than a missing test.

3.  **Recalculate, don't patch.** When a rule changes, the hand
    calculation is redone from scratch for every affected case. Patching
    a single intermediate value risks propagation errors.

4.  **Two-person verification for new oracles.** Any new hand
    calculation or expected value should be independently verified. At
    minimum, AI generates and human verifies, or vice versa.

5.  **Assumption traceability.** Every expected value that depends on an
    assumption (Q-CALC-01 through Q-CALC-04) is tagged with the
    assumption reference. When the assumption is confirmed or corrected
    by DERP, all dependent expected values are recalculated.

3.3 Test Fixture Schema

Test fixtures use a structured JSON format that contains complete
inputs, all expected outputs, and oracle metadata:

> {
>
> \"case_id\": \"case1-robert-martinez\",
>
> \"oracle\": {
>
> \"source\": \"case1-robert-martinez-calculation.md\",
>
> \"verified_by\": \"Jeff (Technical Director)\",
>
> \"verified_date\": \"2026-02-21\",
>
> \"assumptions\": \[\"Q-CALC-01\", \"Q-CALC-04\"\]
>
> },
>
> \"inputs\": {
>
> \"member\": { \... complete member profile \... },
>
> \"employment\": \[ \... full history \... \],
>
> \"salary\": \[ \... all records \... \]
>
> },
>
> \"expected\": {
>
> \"tier\": 1,
>
> \"eligibility\": { \"type\": \"rule_of_75\", \... },
>
> \"ams\": { \"window_months\": 36, \"amount\": \... },
>
> \"benefit\": { \"unreduced\": \..., \"reduced\": \... },
>
> \"payment_options\": { \... all four \... },
>
> \"death_benefit\": { \"lump_sum\": 5000.00, \... }
>
> }
>
> }

